{
  "What is sin(pi/6)?": "",
  "sqrt(3)/2": "",
  "sqrt(2)/2": "",
  "1": "",
  "1/2": "",
  "On the unit circle, pi/6 (30 degrees) corresponds to the point (sqrt(3)/2, 1/2). Since sine is the y-coordinate, sin(pi/6) = 1/2.": "",
  "What is cos(pi/3)?": "",
  "0": "",
  "On the unit circle, pi/3 (60 degrees) corresponds to the point (1/2, sqrt(3)/2). Since cosine is the x-coordinate, cos(pi/3) = 1/2.": "",
  "What is tan(pi/4)?": "",
  "undefined": "",
  "tan(pi/4) = sin(pi/4) / cos(pi/4) = (sqrt(2)/2) / (sqrt(2)/2) = 1. At 45 degrees, sine and cosine are equal, making tangent equal to 1.": "",
  "What is sin(pi/2)?": "",
  "-1": "",
  "At pi/2 (90 degrees), the point on the unit circle is (0, 1). Since sine is the y-coordinate, sin(pi/2) = 1.": "",
  "What is cos(pi)?": "",
  "-1/2": "",
  "At pi (180 degrees), the point on the unit circle is (-1, 0). Since cosine is the x-coordinate, cos(pi) = -1.": "",
  "In which quadrant are both sine and cosine negative?": "",
  "Quadrant II": "",
  "Quadrant IV": "",
  "Quadrant III": "",
  "Quadrant I": "",
  "In Quadrant III (180 to 270 degrees), both x and y coordinates are negative, making both cosine and sine negative. The mnemonic 'All Students Take Calculus' helps remember which functions are positive in each quadrant.": "",
  "What is sin(5pi/6)?": "",
  "-sqrt(3)/2": "",
  "5pi/6 is in Quadrant II with reference angle pi/6. Sine is positive in Quadrant II, so sin(5pi/6) = sin(pi/6) = 1/2.": "",
  "What is cos(7pi/6)?": "",
  "7pi/6 is in Quadrant III with reference angle pi/6. Cosine is negative in Quadrant III, so cos(7pi/6) = -cos(pi/6) = -sqrt(3)/2.": "",
  "What is the value of tan(3pi/4)?": "",
  "sqrt(3)": "",
  "3pi/4 is in Quadrant II with reference angle pi/4. Tangent is negative in Quadrant II, so tan(3pi/4) = -tan(pi/4) = -1.": "",
  "On the unit circle, the coordinates of the point at angle theta are:": "",
  "(tan theta, sec theta)": "",
  "(sin theta, cos theta)": "",
  "(cos theta, sin theta)": "",
  "(1, theta)": "",
  "On the unit circle with radius 1, any angle theta corresponds to the point (cos theta, sin theta). The x-coordinate gives cosine and the y-coordinate gives sine.": "",
  "What is the unit circle?": "",
  "Any circle used for measuring angles": "",
  "A circle with circumference 1": "",
  "A circle centered at the origin with radius 1": "",
  "A circle with area 1": "",
  "The unit circle is a circle centered at the origin (0, 0) with radius 1. It is the fundamental tool for defining trigonometric functions for all angles, not just acute angles in triangles.": "",
  "What does 'sine' represent on the unit circle?": "",
  "The y-coordinate of the point where the terminal side intersects the unit circle": "",
  "The x-coordinate of the point on the unit circle": "",
  "The radius of the circle": "",
  "The angle measured in degrees": "",
  "On the unit circle, sine of an angle equals the y-coordinate of the point where the terminal side of the angle intersects the circle. This definition extends sine to all real numbers.": "",
  "What does 'cosine' represent on the unit circle?": "",
  "The y-coordinate of the point on the unit circle": "",
  "The slope of the terminal side": "",
  "The x-coordinate of the point where the terminal side intersects the unit circle": "",
  "The length of the arc": "",
  "On the unit circle, cosine of an angle equals the x-coordinate of the point where the terminal side of the angle intersects the circle. Cosine and sine together give the full coordinates of the point.": "",
  "What does the tangent function represent?": "",
  "The ratio of sine to cosine: tan(theta) = sin(theta)/cos(theta)": "",
  "The reciprocal of sine": "",
  "The product of sine and cosine": "",
  "The ratio of cosine to sine": "",
  "The tangent function is defined as the ratio of sine to cosine: tan(theta) = sin(theta)/cos(theta). On the unit circle, this equals the y-coordinate divided by the x-coordinate, or the slope of the terminal side.": "",
  "What is the secant function?": "",
  "The reciprocal of cosine: sec(theta) = 1/cos(theta)": "",
  "The reciprocal of tangent": "",
  "The same as cosine": "",
  "The secant function is the reciprocal of cosine: sec(theta) = 1/cos(theta). It is undefined wherever cosine equals zero (at pi/2 + n*pi for integer n).": "",
  "What is the cosecant function?": "",
  "The reciprocal of sine: csc(theta) = 1/sin(theta)": "",
  "The same as sine squared": "",
  "The reciprocal of cosine": "",
  "The cosecant function is the reciprocal of sine: csc(theta) = 1/sin(theta). It is undefined wherever sine equals zero (at n*pi for integer n).": "",
  "What is the cotangent function?": "",
  "The reciprocal of tangent: cot(theta) = cos(theta)/sin(theta)": "",
  "The same as tangent squared": "",
  "The cotangent function is the reciprocal of tangent: cot(theta) = cos(theta)/sin(theta) = 1/tan(theta). It is undefined wherever sine equals zero.": "",
  "What does the mnemonic 'SOH-CAH-TOA' stand for?": "",
  "Sine = Hypotenuse/Opposite, Cosine = Hypotenuse/Adjacent, Tangent = Adjacent/Opposite": "",
  "Sine = Opposite/Adjacent, Cosine = Adjacent/Opposite, Tangent = Hypotenuse/Opposite": "",
  "Sine = Opposite/Hypotenuse, Cosine = Adjacent/Hypotenuse, Tangent = Opposite/Adjacent": "",
  "Sine = Adjacent/Hypotenuse, Cosine = Opposite/Hypotenuse, Tangent = Adjacent/Opposite": "",
  "SOH-CAH-TOA helps remember the right-triangle definitions: Sine = Opposite/Hypotenuse, Cosine = Adjacent/Hypotenuse, Tangent = Opposite/Adjacent.": "",
  "What does 'ASTC' (All Students Take Calculus) help you remember?": "",
  "The order of operations for solving equations": "",
  "Which trigonometric functions are positive in each quadrant": "",
  "The formulas for arc length and sector area": "",
  "The values of sine at special angles": "",
  "ASTC tells which trig functions are positive: All in QI, Sine in QII, Tangent in QIII, Cosine in QIV. This is essential for evaluating trig functions of angles beyond the first quadrant.": "",
  "What is a 'special angle' in trigonometry?": "",
  "An angle whose trigonometric values can be determined exactly, such as 30, 45, and 60 degrees": "",
  "An angle expressed only in radians": "",
  "Any angle greater than 90 degrees": "",
  "An angle that cannot be measured": "",
  "Special angles (30, 45, 60 degrees or pi/6, pi/4, pi/3 radians) have exact trigonometric values involving simple fractions and square roots. These values come from the 30-60-90 and 45-45-90 right triangles.": "",
  "A surveyor needs to find the height of a building. Standing 50 meters from the base, the angle of elevation to the top is 60 degrees. Using tan(60) = sqrt(3), what is the height of the building?": "",
  "25sqrt(3) meters": "",
  "50 meters": "",
  "100 meters": "",
  "50sqrt(3) meters": "",
  "Using tan(60) = opposite/adjacent = height/50: height = 50 * tan(60) = 50 * sqrt(3) = 50sqrt(3) meters, approximately 86.6 meters.": "",
  "A ramp makes a 30-degree angle with the ground. If the ramp is 20 feet long, how high does it rise? Use sin(30) = 1/2.": "",
  "10 feet": "",
  "10sqrt(3) feet": "",
  "5 feet": "",
  "20 feet": "",
  "Using sin(30) = opposite/hypotenuse = height/20: height = 20 * sin(30) = 20 * (1/2) = 10 feet. The ramp rises 10 feet vertically.": "",
  "A helicopter hovers at a point such that the angle of depression to a landing pad 200 meters away horizontally is 45 degrees. What is the helicopter's altitude? Use tan(45) = 1.": "",
  "200sqrt(2) meters": "",
  "200 meters": "",
  "400 meters": "",
  "The angle of depression equals the angle of elevation from the pad. Using tan(45) = altitude/200: altitude = 200 * tan(45) = 200 * 1 = 200 meters.": "",
  "A pendulum swings to a maximum angle of pi/6 radians from the vertical. If the pendulum is 2 meters long, what is the horizontal displacement at maximum swing? Use sin(pi/6) = 1/2.": "",
  "1 meter": "",
  "sqrt(3) meters": "",
  "2 meters": "",
  "0.5 meters": "",
  "The horizontal displacement = length * sin(angle) = 2 * sin(pi/6) = 2 * (1/2) = 1 meter. The pendulum moves 1 meter horizontally from the rest position.": "",
  "A ladder leans against a wall making a 60-degree angle with the ground. If the foot of the ladder is 4 meters from the wall, how long is the ladder? Use cos(60) = 1/2.": "",
  "4 meters": "",
  "8 meters": "",
  "4sqrt(3) meters": "",
  "Using cos(60) = adjacent/hypotenuse = 4/ladder: ladder = 4/cos(60) = 4/(1/2) = 8 meters.": "",
  "A ship sails 10 km on a bearing such that it ends up at a point where the angle from north is pi/3 radians east. How far east has the ship traveled? Use sin(pi/3) = sqrt(3)/2.": "",
  "10 km": "",
  "5 km": "",
  "5sqrt(3) km": "",
  "10sqrt(3) km": "",
  "The eastward displacement = distance * sin(angle) = 10 * sin(pi/3) = 10 * (sqrt(3)/2) = 5sqrt(3) km, approximately 8.66 km.": "",
  "An engineer designs a roof with a pitch angle of pi/4 radians. If the roof must span 12 meters horizontally (6 meters on each side from the peak), how tall is the peak of the roof? Use tan(pi/4) = 1.": "",
  "3 meters": "",
  "6sqrt(2) meters": "",
  "12 meters": "",
  "6 meters": "",
  "Using tan(pi/4) = height / half-span: height = 6 * tan(pi/4) = 6 * 1 = 6 meters. The peak of the roof is 6 meters high.": "",
  "A kite is flying at the end of a 100-meter string that makes a 30-degree angle with the ground. How high above the ground is the kite? Use sin(30) = 1/2.": "",
  "25 meters": "",
  "Height = string length * sin(angle) = 100 * sin(30) = 100 * (1/2) = 50 meters. The kite flies 50 meters above the ground.": "",
  "A Ferris wheel has a radius of 20 meters and its center is 25 meters above the ground. When a rider is at an angle of 2pi/3 from the rightmost point (3 o'clock), what is their height above the ground? Use sin(2pi/3) = sqrt(3)/2.": "",
  "25 + 10sqrt(3) meters": "",
  "45 meters": "",
  "25 + 20sqrt(3) meters": "",
  "Height = center height + radius * sin(angle) = 25 + 20 * sin(2pi/3) = 25 + 20 * (sqrt(3)/2) = 25 + 10sqrt(3) meters, approximately 42.3 meters.": "",
  "An airplane takes off at a 15-degree angle. After flying 2000 meters along its flight path, what is its altitude? Use sin(15) approximately equal to 0.259.": "",
  "1000 meters": "",
  "750 meters": "",
  "259 meters": "",
  "518 meters": "",
  "Altitude = flight distance * sin(angle) = 2000 * sin(15) = 2000 * 0.259 = 518 meters. The airplane reaches an altitude of approximately 518 meters.": ""
